Imagine the black hole spinning around an axis; instead of collapsing into a single point, the intense gravitational forces and angular momentum spread out the singularity into a ring. This ring is infinitesimally thin and lies in the equatorial plane of the rotating black hole.

This difference in geometry between the Schwarzschild and Kerr black holes highlights how rotation fundamentally changes the structure of a black hole's singularity. It can be a bit more challenging to visualize compared to the point singularity, but thinking of it as a thin ring can help conceptualize how the Kerr black holeâ€™s singularity is distributed.

